Let \varphi be a formula with at most x,y free such that the following two conditions hold:
\forall a.\mkern 5mu\exists b.\mkern 5mu\varphi (a,b);
\forall a,b,b'.\mkern 5mu\varphi (a,b) \wedge \varphi (a,b') \Rightarrow b = b'. Then for any set A, there is a function f with \mathsf {dom}(f) = A such that f(a) = b \Leftrightarrow \varphi (a,b).

A set N is called a natural number set if it is equipped with

an element 0 \in  N;

a successor function s\colon N\to N.
  These data are subject to the following requirements.

s\colon N\to N is injective;

non-looping: for every x \in  N, s(x) \neq  0;

induction principle: for every set P \subseteq  N, if 0 \in  P and for all x \in  N, x \in  P implies that s(x) \in  P then P = N.

Let X be a set, x_{0} \in X, and h\colon X\to X be a function. For each n \in \mathbb {N}, a function g\colon s(n)\to X is called an n-germ if it satisfies the following conditions:
g(0) = x_{0};
g(s(m)) = h(g(m)) for all m < n.

Let \varphi be a definable mapping with at most x,y free and x_{0} be an arbitrary set. A class-level n-germ is a function g with \mathsf {dom}(g) = s(n) such that the following two conditions are satisfied.
g(0) = x_{0};
\varphi (g(m),g(s(m))) for all m < n.

In the induction step, the induction hypothesis says there is a unique n-germ g_{n}\colon s(n)\to X.
    Consider the function g_{s(n)}\colon s(s(n))\to X defined by
           g_{s(n)}(k) =       \begin {cases}         h(g_{n}(n)) & \text {if $k = s(n)$}\\         g_{n}(k) & \text {if $k < s(n)$}       \end {cases}

Let X be a set equipped with a distinguished element x_{0} \in X and an endofunction h\colon X\to X. Then there is a unique function f\colon \mathbb {N}\to X such that
f(0) = x_{0};
f(s(n)) = h(f(n)).

Let \varphi be a definable mapping with at most x,y free. Then for any set x_{0} there is a unique function f with \mathsf {dom}(f) = \mathbb {N} such that
f(0) = x_{0};
\varphi (f(n),f(s(n))) for every n \in \mathbb {N}.

In the induction step, the induction hypothesis says there is a unique n-germ g_{n}\colon s(n)\to X.
    Consider the function g_{s(n)}\colon s(s(n))\to X defined by
           g_{s(n)}(k) =       \begin {cases}         h(g_{n}(n)) & \text {if $k = s(n)$}\\         g_{n}(k) & \text {if $k < s(n)$}       \end {cases}
